if an error bit occurs there. As shown in Fig. 3, the variable nodes in the red dashed line connect to the 12 check nodes, whereas the remaining variable nodes are connected to fewer check nodes. If a burst error occurs at the red part, the probability of data recovery is low.
The regular interleaving methods such as byte interleaving (i.e., data is packed in rows and sent in columns) [11] or permutation of random bits are almost ineffective when applied to LPDC code. It is because the ability of data recovery depends on the number of affected check nodes by noise, as is indicated by the number of bit ‘1’ in equation (3). Also, as shown in Fig. 3, a lot of check nodes is affected when the error bits occur in part 1.

